picks.reasoning: With the very first pick we want the single biggest points-ceiling asset at the scarcest position. Haaland is a proven 20-30-goal striker in a dominant Man City attack and clearly projects above every other forward on the board, whereas elite midfield scores (Salah, Saka, Palmer, Son, etc.) are still plentiful for our next turn. Locking in Haaland gives us a weekly set-and-forget starter up front and lets us build the midfield depth later where the talent pool remains deep.

We need to start building a strong midfield core and Ødegaard offers an elite, nailed-on 90-minute attacker for Arsenal with proven FPL output and set-piece duty. While Marmoush ranks slightly higher, his minutes at Man City are uncertain and we already own a City asset (Haaland). Ødegaard gives us reliability, captaincy upside in plum fixtures, and keeps our Man City slots flexible for later value picks. Securing a premium, dependable midfielder now lets us use our immediate Round 3 pick (coming next) to address another position before the talent pool thins.

We still need four more midfielders and very few top-tier options remain. Mbeumo is a proven FPL points-getter and now joins a stronger Man United attack, offering both goal and assist upside with nailed minutes and penalty duties. He’s the highest-quality, lowest-risk asset left in the elite tier (rank 14) and will likely be snapped up before our next pick at 28, whereas no defender or goalkeeper is being drafted yet and plenty of solid options will still be there in 12 picks’ time.

We have no defenders yet and must fill five spots; locking in the highest-upside DEF on the board is critical before the run on the position starts. Frimpong’s move to Liverpool puts him in a strong defence while his wing-back style offers big attacking returns, giving premium value in one pick. We can address forward or another need with our immediate next pick at 29, but securing this scarce top-tier defender now protects us from being left short at the back.

We only have one forward (Haaland) and need two more, while quality strikers are thinning out fast. Evanilson is the highest-ranked forward left (36), arrives as Bournemouth’s record signing and is nailed to start, offering secure minutes and a good xG profile. With 12 picks before we draft again several managers still need strikers, so a forward run is likely; top defenders should still be available (Gabriel, Saliba, Virgil, Robertson, etc.) next time. Locking in Evanilson now secures a strong FWD2 and keeps roster balance.

A mini-run on premium defenders has started (Robertson, Saliba, Gvardiol just went) and we only own one DEF so far. Van Dijk (“Virgil”) is the last nailed-on, 90-minute elite option from a top-four back-line still on the board, giving us clean-sheet stability to balance Frimpong’s attacking risk. Because we pick again immediately at 43, we can address midfield or forward next, so locking in this cornerstone defender now maximises squad structure and value.

Midfield is our biggest remaining need and Arsenal’s Martinelli offers a nailed-on starting spot in a top-three attack with high goal/assist potential. He’s better FPL value and more secure minutes than higher-ranked names like Kluivert or Schade, and he will almost certainly be gone before our next turn in 13 picks. We can still address keeper, extra defenders and our bench forward later, as plenty of options remain at those positions.

Best value on the board (rank 39), fills a midfield slot we still need, and offers high upside in Man City’s attack. Goalkeepers and extra defenders can be taken later, while elite attacking options will dry up quickly, so locking in Savinho now maximises points potential before we use our immediate next pick on a forward or other need.

Forward depth is thin in a 7-team draft and several managers still need strikers. Richarlison is the highest-ranked FWD left (63) and should lead the line for an attack-minded Spurs side even after Kudus’ arrival. Securing our third starting forward now locks in a weekly starter before a likely mini run on strikers, while quality mids and goalkeepers (e.g. Ederson, Pickford, Rice, Doku) are still plentiful and more likely to last until our next pick at 70.

He’s the highest-ranked player left on the board (45), immediately completes our midfield quota, and offers goal-scoring upside in an Everton side that badly needs creativity – meaning he should be nailed for minutes and bonus. Because we pick again at 71 we can address defence or goalkeeper straight away, so locking in the best value mid now maximises roster strength while the deeper DEF/GKP pools remain plentiful.

We still need three more defenders and two goalkeepers.  Quality defenders who are guaranteed starters at elite clean-sheet clubs will disappear quickest, while there are still plenty of serviceable keepers left.  “Rúben” (Dias) is Manchester City’s nailed-on centre-back, offers 38-game security and consistent clean-sheet/bonus potential, and gives us coverage from a second top-tier defence to balance our double-Liverpool back line.  The other high-rank defenders (James, Timber) carry significant injury/rotation risk, and solid goalkeepers such as Sánchez, Pope or Vicario should still be available 12 picks from now.  Locking in City defensive reliability here maximises value and lets us address goalkeeper in the next turn.

We still need two reliable defenders and Ben White offers the best mix of nailed-on minutes, clean-sheet potential and occasional attacking returns in the pool. Arsenal’s defence is among the league’s strongest, and White is more rotation-proof than the similarly-ranked Man City options while carrying higher upside than Branthwaite (Everton’s weaker CS outlook). Because we hold the very next pick as well, we can safely lock in this high-value defender now and address goalkeeper with pick 85, when several comparable keepers will still be on the board.

We still have zero goalkeepers and only three picks left, so locking in a nailed-on starter is priority #1. Guglielmo Vicario is Spurs’ clear No. 1, offers strong clean-sheet and save potential, and is less rotation-prone than Sánchez (risk of Petrović) or any of the Man City backups. Top-rank defenders like Branthwaite will probably still have decent alternatives in 13 picks’ time, whereas quality starting keepers could dry up quickly with several rivals still needing one or two. Securing Vicario now gives us a safe GK anchor and lets us address the final DEF and second GK with our last two selections.

We still need one defender and one backup keeper. With two back-to-back picks (98 and 99) we can lock both positions in, so we’ll first grab the clear-standout defender on the board. John Stones (rank 161) gives elite clean-sheet potential, occasional attacking returns in Pep’s inverted role and pairs well with our already-owned Rúben Dias. Because we already have four nailed defenders, we can absorb his rotation risk and take the high upside, then use pick 99 for the safer goalkeeper option.

We still need a second goalkeeper and most of the highest-ranked options left (Trafford, Ortega) are likely understudies at Manchester City, offering limited minutes. Alphonse Areola is West Ham’s clear No.1, giving us guaranteed starts, plenty of save/bonus potential, and good fixture rotation with Vicario for tougher Spurs games or possible blanks. Securing a nailed-on starter now is safer than gambling on a backup who might never play.

Taking the #1 ranked player and most consistent Fantasy performer. Salah has delivered 200+ points in multiple seasons and remains Liverpool's primary attacking threat and penalty taker. With 5 MID spots to fill, securing the most reliable midfielder available is the optimal strategy.

Highest-ranked forward available at rank 13. With 5 top forwards already taken, I need to secure quality forwards early. Bowen is West Ham's key attacking player and offers consistent returns. Forward depth is more limited than midfielder depth at this stage.

Best available player at rank 10, recently transferred to Man City which should boost his output. Need to secure quality attacking players before focusing on filling positional gaps with lower-ranked but serviceable defenders and goalkeeper.
Best available player by rank (28) and adds quality depth to midfield. Liverpool assets are reliable FPL performers and securing premium talent early is crucial in draft format.
High-quality midfielder (rank 30) who just transferred to Newcastle for £55m, indicating his value. Need 2 more midfielders and he's one of the best available at this pick position.

High-quality Man City defender (rank 81) who provides attacking threat and clean sheet potential. With 5 DEF positions to fill, securing premium defensive assets early is crucial before they're all taken.

Kluivert at rank 33 is exceptional value and the best available midfielder by a significant margin. With only needing one more midfielder, securing this quality player now is crucial before he's taken by another manager. Can address GKP and DEF needs in later rounds where more options remain.

Best available forward by ranking (55) and represents excellent value. Need to secure quality forwards while available as the pool drops off significantly. Fulham's consistent performance makes him a reliable pick.

Best available forward by far at rank 64, fills critical position need. Man United striker should get regular minutes and scoring opportunities. Quality drop-off to next forwards is significant while I have more viable defensive/GK options remaining.

Need to secure a quality goalkeeper while still available. Sels is Nottingham Forest's #1 keeper with the best rank (209) among available goalkeepers. Forest has been defensively solid this season, making him a reliable pick for this position.
Need a quality starting goalkeeper to pair with Sels. Pope is Newcastle's established #1 with strong Premier League experience and fewer quality GK options remaining compared to defenders.
Best available defender at rank 131, Arsenal's strong defensive system and attacking returns potential, plus positional versatility make him excellent value for completing my defensive line

Highest-ranked available defender at 134. Young Everton centre-back with strong defensive potential and good value for a team that will defend frequently. Best available option to fill my defensive needs.

Fulham's attacking left-back offers good value at pick 97. More reliable than injury-prone Stones, and his wingback role provides attacking upside. Fulham's defensive solidity under Silva makes him a safe floor play while maintaining ceiling for returns.
Best available defender by rank (170), plays for defensively strong Man City, and as a recent signing likely to get opportunities. Fills my final roster spot with highest upside potential.

Highest-ranked available player at rank 3. As Chelsea's main creative force and penalty taker, Palmer offers elite production. With 5 MID spots to fill vs only 3 FWD spots, securing a premium midfielder early provides better roster flexibility. His consistency and high ceiling make him the optimal pick at this position.

Elite midfielder ranked 9th overall, just transferred to Liverpool for £100m+. Best player available by far. Securing two premium midfielders early provides a strong foundation while quality forwards and defenders are still available in later rounds.
Elite midfielder ranked 15th provides exceptional value at this stage. With Palmer and Wirtz secured, adding Cunha creates a dominant midfield trio before pivoting to forwards and defenders.
Top-ranked midfielder available at rank 25, offers excellent value as a proven Premier League performer who can provide consistent returns as a 4th/5th midfielder in the squad.

Rogers is the highest-ranked midfielder available at 29, offering excellent value for a 5th round pick. As an Aston Villa player in a strong team, he provides good potential for assists and goals to complement my midfield.
Best available forward at rank 46, proven Premier League striker with consistent returns. Need to prioritize filling the 3 FWD positions with quality options before they're gone.
Best available forward at rank 48, fills critical position need with only 1 FWD on roster. Strong option from Wolves who should provide consistent returns.
Top-ranked forward available at 50, fills my last FWD slot with a Chelsea striker who offers good value and potential upside.
Elite attacking fullback at Liverpool with rank 83 - best defensive value available by far. His attacking returns and Liverpool's strong defense make him a premium pick at this stage.
Best available defender at rank 117, significantly higher quality than other defensive options. Crystal Palace defender offers attacking potential and good value at this stage of the draft.
Arsenal's young left-back offers great value at rank 120 and provides versatility. With Liverpool signing multiple attackers, Arsenal defenders could see more clean sheet opportunities.
Top-ranked defender available at 130, solid Nottingham Forest player who will provide consistent returns. Need to secure quality defenders before the pool dries up further.

Schär is the highest-ranked defender available at 137, providing good value as my final defender. With Newcastle's solid defensive structure and his regular playing time, he offers better potential than other available options.

As Fulham's established starter with a solid defensive record, Leno offers the best combination of playing time guarantee and quality among available goalkeepers, crucial for filling my final two GKP slots.
Best available goalkeeper at rank 220, plays for Man City which provides potential for clean sheets despite limited minutes. Much better value than alternatives like Ortega (244) or Bayindir (247).

With Haaland, Salah, and Palmer off the board, Saka is the highest quality remaining premium attacker, nailed in Arsenal's XI, with strong goal and assist output, and possible penalties. His combination of safety, upside, and flexibility (midfielder in FPL, can also be a captaincy option) make him the optimal pick here, especially in such a small league where securing elite midfielders is crucial. While Isak and Watkins are great FWD options, there is more forward depth than elite midfielders in the current pool, so positional value leans Saka.

Son Heung-min offers elite, proven FPL output and positional flexibility (MID/FWD), and secures my 2nd premium midfielder after Saka, while top-tier forwards like Bowen could still be available at my next pick. Son's track record, nailed role at Spurs, and exceptional FPL ceiling make him superior to similarly ranked mids (Wirtz, Marmoush) and more valuable than any available forward at this stage in a 7-team league, where locking in two premium mids provides a weekly advantage.

I have two elite midfielders (Saka, Son) but no forwards. In a 7-team draft, securing a lead forward from a top side is crucial due to scarcity and positional requirements. 'Solanke' is now with Spurs according to the list, meaning strong attacking potential, supplied by a creative team, with high minutes and reliable gametime. Other top forwards (Watkins, Isak, Ekitiké, Gyökeres, Bowen, Cunha, Mbeumo) have already been taken, making forward depth thin. The next best forwards are significant steps down in reliability and upside. With strong midfield already, prioritizing striker now better suits flexibility before defensive or keeper runs begin. 'Solanke' maximizes both value and positional scarcity at this stage.

With only one forward currently in the squad (Solanke) and the requirement to play at least one each week, it’s critical to secure another quality striker while supply is good. Mateta is the highest-ranked available forward and offers strong value as Palace’s main striker. Midfield depth remains high on the board (with Gibbs-White, Gakpo, etc. still available), so it’s safer to secure a forward now before the pool dries up. This keeps roster balance and flexibility for later rounds when midfielders and defenders are more plentiful.

At this stage, I need to strengthen my midfield depth, which remains a premium position in a 7-team league, and Maddison offers significant upside. He's first choice, settled at Spurs, and has the potential to deliver returns similar to higher-drafted mids. Defenders and goalkeepers can be targeted in coming rounds, as there are many quality options left and others seem focused on rounding out midfield and attack. Maddison is a proven FPL asset and fits my team’s need for another reliable starting midfielder.

I need to start filling my defense, and with 'Saliba' (rank 84) available, I'm grabbing a nailed and high-upside Arsenal starter who offers clean sheet potential and occasional attacking threat. He represents strong value at this pick, especially as defenders are starting to come off the board (see Gabriel and Robertson just picked). Given his team context and reliability, he could anchor my defense, and waiting longer risks missing out on top-tier defensive options as other managers also need to fill their back lines soon.

At this stage, I already have a solid midfield core but still need to fill two more spots and maximize starter quality. 'Trossard' is a versatile Arsenal midfielder/forward with real attacking threat and likely starting minutes after Arsenal's summer business. He’s one of the best available midfielders still on the board, offers some goal and assist potential, and helps to ensure I don’t miss out on the best available mids as teams fill up their starting XIs. Given the remaining defenders and goalkeepers, I can wait on those positions for a round or two without losing significant value, so strengthening my midfield with a proven Premier League asset is ideal here.

Mitoma offers significant attacking upside, consistent starts for Brighton, and FPL pedigree. He fills the final required midfield slot with a high-floor, high-ceiling player. Although there are a few midfielders ranked slightly higher, Mitoma's proven track record and nailed-on status makes him a safer pick for both immediate and long-term value. Midfield options get thin fast in 7-team drafts, and with so many teams filling their mid rotations, this is a critical spot to secure a top-50, Premier League-proven starter. Defensive depth and goalkeepers can still be targeted in the next rounds, where the difference in quality is less stark.

At this stage, I need to build out my defense after focusing heavily on midfield and attack in early rounds. 'Pedro Porro' of Spurs offers proven Premier League quality, strong attacking returns for a defender, and is nailed in a good team with improving clean sheet potential. He is higher value than most available defenders, offers more upside than other defensive options, and defenders will likely start flying off the board soon given how thin the top tier is. I can address goalkeeper or backup forwards in the next rounds, but Porro could easily be my top-scoring defender after Saliba.

With only one goalkeeper (Ederson M.) ranked inside the top 130 still available, and three of the six other managers already selecting a goalkeeper over the last two rounds, it is strategically wise to lock in a premium starting GK from a top team (Man City). This gives reliability in a position where alternatives quickly become unreliable as the pool thins, and keeps flexibility for later rounds to chase outfield upside, since GKP scarcity can be a pain point. Only 2 GKP spots remain unfilled on your roster, so you can wait on a backup; take the clear first choice now.

With strong attacking and midfield depth, my top priority is defense. 'Tarkowski' is a nailed-on starter and set-piece threat for Everton, one of the most reliable defenders available. While his team is not elite, his appearance assurance, aerial ability, and bonus potential make him higher value than defenders of top clubs who rotate (e.g., 'J.Timber', 'James'). There is risk others will begin shoring up defense soon, and this pick is best for both floor and availability.

I need to fill another forward slot and 'Barry' is the highest-ranked available forward (rank 87), playing for Everton. Considering that the next available forwards have slightly lower draft value and there’s a high risk that others will take the better strikers soon as teams fill out their squads, Barry is the best balance between immediate positional need and player value. I can return to strengthen my defense in upcoming rounds where quality options like Timber, Branthwaite, and Schär should still be available, but the drop-off at forward becomes steep quickly in a seven-team draft pool.

With two defender spots still needed, selecting 'Matheus N.' (Matheus Nunes) from Man City offers strong value. He is the highest-ranked available defender, plays for a top club likely to secure clean sheets, and offers potential attacking returns given City's style. While Man City rotation risk exists, the ceiling is notably higher than with most other available defenders. Goalkeeper depth can be addressed with the next pick, as many remain. This balances positional need, player quality, and maximizing value at this stage.

Aké is the highest-ranked available defender (158) and a regular starter for Manchester City, a team known for its strong defensive record. He offers attacking threat on set pieces and is a flexible asset, covering both center-back and left-back roles. While there are other intriguing options, Aké's combination of playing time, clean sheet potential, and club context makes him the clear best value at this pick for rounding out my defense.

Ortega Moreno is the clear standout among the remaining goalkeepers, both in player quality and potential FPL upside. He is currently Ederson's backup at Man City, so he offers perfect handcuff/insurance if Ederson were to get injured or rotated. No starter is truly left in this pool, so maximizing value at this spot means locking up one of the league's best defenses for all situations. Additionally, selecting an alternative like José Sá or Verbruggen offers less upside and team cover. Given your strong outfield, maximizing security at goalkeeper is priority.

With Haaland and the top tier of midfielders already gone, securing an elite and reliable forward is a priority. Watkins was incredible last season, serving as the durable and consistent talisman for a strong Aston Villa attack. He provides a guaranteed source of goals and assists, anchoring my forward line and addressing the scarcity of top-tier strikers.

Foden was the Premier League Player of the Season and is a core attacker for the best team in the league. Getting him at pick 10 is incredible value, and he provides a high-ceiling cornerstone for my midfield which currently has no players.

With top-tier forwards becoming scarce, securing Havertz is a strategic move. He was a key goal contributor for an elite Arsenal offense in the second half of last season and is classified as a forward. This provides a strong attacking foundation alongside Watkins and Foden, locking down two premium forward spots from top teams early in the draft.

I need to build out my midfield, and Gordon represents the best value available. He was a top-tier fantasy asset last season with 11 goals and 10 assists in a strong Newcastle side. While there is new competition, his established role and proven output in the Premier League make him a safer and more reliable pick than other midfielders available. This adds a second high-quality midfielder to my roster alongside Foden.

My roster is currently strong in attack but has zero defenders. It's crucial to secure an elite defensive anchor before a run on top defenders begins. Gabriel is a nailed-on starter for what is arguably the best defense in the league, offering both high clean sheet potential and significant goal threat from set pieces. Picking him now provides a high-floor, high-ceiling foundation for my backline, addressing a major positional need with a premium asset.

Securing an elite attacking defender from a top side at this stage of the draft is incredible value. Robertson has a proven track record of delivering both defensive and attacking returns at the highest level. With four defender slots to fill and only one currently occupied, this pick addresses a major positional need with a premium, set-and-forget asset. Given the number of teams needing defenders and goalkeepers, waiting would risk missing out on the top tier of talent in these scarcer positions.

It is highly unusual for Round 7 to begin with every top-tier goalkeeper still available. I am capitalizing on this market inefficiency to draft the consensus best goalkeeper in the league. This move secures a reliable, high-scoring player at a position where a run is imminent. While elite defenders like Trippier and Porro are tempting, the opportunity to get the undisputed #1 at a '1 of 1' position is too valuable to pass up. I can address my other needs with my upcoming picks from a deep pool of available outfield players.

The value for Darwin at this stage of the draft is too immense to pass up. Despite some rotation risk, his underlying statistics are elite, and he plays for one of the most potent attacks in the league. Securing him completes an incredibly strong forward line with Watkins and Havertz, giving my team a massive ceiling. While I still need midfielders, the drop-off in quality at the forward position feels more significant, and I'm confident I can acquire quality midfielders in the upcoming rounds.

I'm picking the best player available who fills a significant positional need. Kudus is the highest-ranked player left on the board and just secured a major transfer to an attacking Spurs side where he should be a focal point. The drop-off in quality to the next available midfielders feels significant, so I want to lock in this high-upside player now. While there is strong value in defense, the pool of available midfielders with Kudus's potential is nearly empty.

I am shocked to see Trippier still available this late in the draft. He addresses my most significant positional need, as I only have two defenders. As Newcastle's primary set-piece taker, he offers elite attacking potential from the back, something that is rare and incredibly valuable in FPL. Despite his low pre-draft ranking here, his proven FPL track record makes him an absolute steal at pick 66 and the clear best player available.

At pick 75, securing a player of Rodrigo's caliber is exceptional value. He is a guaranteed starter for the best team in the league and was one of the highest-scoring midfielders in FPL last season. Despite his deeper role, he consistently provides goals, assists, and significant bonus points, offering a high and reliable floor. This pick adds a core of consistent points to my midfield, balancing out other higher-risk, high-reward players on my roster. Given the talent drop-off in midfield, he is the clear best player available.

I need one more starting midfielder to complete a very strong unit. Szoboszlai represents incredible value at pick 80. He is a key creative player and a guaranteed starter for a potent Liverpool attack. He has multiple avenues for points through goals, assists, and set-piece duties, offering both a high floor and a high ceiling. This pick diversifies my squad, adding a second player from an elite offensive team.

I already own Alisson Becker, and Liverpool just invested a significant fee to bring in Mamardashvili. This pick allows me to handcuff my goalkeeper position for the entire season, guaranteeing a starting Liverpool keeper every gameweek. This is a classic, high-value draft strategy. The pool of quality defenders is still deep, so I am confident I can secure a good one with my next pick, whereas the unique strategic value of this pick will not be available later.

Udogie is a high-upside attacking fullback who is a nailed-on starter for a top-half team. He was a fantastic FPL asset last season, and his rank of 354 represents incredible value at this stage of the draft. This pick significantly strengthens my defensive unit with a player who offers both clean sheet potential and attacking returns.

This is an incredible value pick to complete my defence. Pau is a guaranteed starter for a top-four, Champions League side in Aston Villa. He offers both clean sheet potential and some goal threat. This pick diversifies my defensive assets, as I have no other Villa players in my backline. Getting a player of his calibre and reliability in the 15th round is a steal that strengthens my squad depth significantly.

Isak is the highest-ranked available player (rank 4) and a premium forward, addressing a position with scarce elite options after Haaland and Watkins were picked. He offers consistent goal-scoring potential for Newcastle, and securing a top FWD early is strategic given the depth in midfield options still available.

B.Fernandes is the highest-ranked available player (rank 7) and a premium midfielder with consistent FPL returns. With forwards being heavily drafted early (5 FWDs taken in first 8 picks), securing a top-tier MID now addresses team needs for midfield strength. Other teams likely to target remaining FWDs like Bowen next, but Fernandes offers better value and scarcity in elite MIDs may increase later. His role at Man Utd remains key despite recent transfers.

João Pedro is the highest-ranked available player (rank 19) and addresses a forward need, providing strong goal potential at Chelsea. With top forwards like Haaland and Watkins already taken, securing him now prevents missing out on elite attacking talent. His recent transfer boosts his value, and I can build midfield and defense depth in later rounds.

Wissa is the highest-ranked available player (rank 22) and fills the remaining forward slot needed for the squad. With only one forward position left to draft, securing a top-tier forward like Wissa adds depth and scoring potential, especially since other teams are actively picking forwards (e.g., Wood in the last pick). Although midfield and defense are also urgent needs, the value here outweighs delaying, as comparable midfielders like Gibbs-White (rank 25) are slightly lower ranked, and defenders/goalkeepers can be targeted in later rounds when more options remain.

Semenyo has the highest rank (31) among available players, indicating strong value and potential for points as a midfielder. With only one midfielder currently on my roster, filling the MID position is critical. Bournemouth's attacking style could yield good returns, and this pick secures a high-value asset before others target similar options. DEF and GKP can be addressed in later rounds as they are less picked so far.

Johnson is a high-value midfielder (rank 34) from Tottenham, addressing the MID position need. He offers strong attacking potential in a top club with recent transfers boosting Spurs' offense. Picking a midfielder now secures quality before others do, as DEF and GKP options are less scarce and can be addressed later.

Prioritizing defense as it's currently empty and critical for meeting lineup requirements (need 3 DEF starters). Cucurella has a strong rank (80), plays for Chelsea, and offers high value with potential clean sheet points. With recent picks focusing on midfielders and goalkeepers starting to be taken (e.g., A.Becker), securing a top defender now mitigates risk of scarcity later. Midfield options are still abundant for future picks.

Schade is the highest-ranked available midfielder (rank 37), providing excellent value and point-scoring potential for Brentford. With only two midfield slots left to fill and midfielders typically scoring more points than defenders or goalkeepers, prioritizing a top-tier MID like Schade strengthens my core. Defenders and goalkeepers are more abundant and can be addressed in later rounds, especially since other managers may focus on those positions next after recent GKP and DEF picks.

Selecting Mac Allister, a high-quality midfielder from Liverpool (rank 58), to complete the single remaining midfield slot. He offers strong attacking potential in a top team and is a reliable starter, providing good FPL value. With higher-ranked midfielders like Cherki being new to Man City and potentially rotation-prone, Mac Allister is a safer pick. Defenders and goalkeepers, which are more abundant and can be filled later, are prioritized for subsequent rounds to manage position needs strategically.

Pickford is the highest-ranked available player (rank 115) and addresses the urgent need for a goalkeeper. With five teams, including mine, still needing goalkeepers, securing a top option like Pickford now prevents missing out on quality GKs as other managers may target them soon. While defenders are also required, there are more viable DEF options available in later rounds, and Pickford's reliability for Everton provides a strong foundation for the position.

Reece James is the highest-ranked available defender (rank 123) with high attacking potential for Chelsea. I need to prioritize strengthening my defense as I only have one defender currently, and James offers the best value and upside compared to other options. Goalkeeper can be addressed later with picks still available.

Hall is the highest-ranked available defender at rank 126, offering strong value for a Newcastle defender with potential for clean sheets and attacking returns. With three defender spots still needed and top options like him likely to be targeted soon by other managers (e.g., claude-sonnet-4 or claude-code could pick defenders next), this addresses the immediate need while diversifying from my current Chelsea defenders (Cucurella and James). Goalkeepers like Sánchez can be prioritized in later rounds as more options remain.

Top available defender with rank 153, fills urgent need for defensive depth given current roster has only three injury-prone defenders. Arsenal's new signing likely to start, and high value outweighs goalkeeper options at this stage.

Prioritized securing a reliable starting goalkeeper as backup to Pickford due to scarcity of quality GKP options and recent draft trends showing GKP being picked quickly (e.g., Sánchez taken just before). Henderson (rank 221) is a solid starter for Crystal Palace with good potential for saves and clean sheets. With only 5 picks until my next selection (pick 99), there's high risk that top GKP like Henderson or Leno could be taken, leaving weaker options. Defender depth is less urgent as I already have 4 DEF for 3 starting spots, and numerous viable DEF options (e.g., Kiwior, Aina) should remain available at pick 99.

Kiwior is the highest-ranked available defender (rank 191) and plays for Arsenal, a top team with strong defensive potential. This pick provides depth and good clean sheet opportunities, while diversifying slightly from existing defenders (Chelsea and Newcastle). With many top defenders already taken, securing the best value here is strategic, especially as other managers may target him next.

With three elite forwards already selected in the first six picks, forwards appear scarce. Ekitiké, a high-profile signing for Liverpool at rank 8, offers excellent value as a top remaining forward option in a strong attacking side, addressing potential position scarcity while securing a near-top ranked player.

Securing a top-tier forward like Gyökeres, who has transferred to Arsenal and ranks highly at 11, addresses my need for another forward early while premiums in this position are being drafted quickly. Midfielders have deeper options available, allowing me to fill those later.

With two premium forwards already secured, I prioritize starting to fill my midfield needs. Eze is the highest-ranked available midfielder with strong creative potential at Crystal Palace, and mids are being drafted quickly, so securing him now addresses a key position while grabbing high value before others do.

Wood is the highest-ranked available player at rank 21, providing excellent value as my final needed forward. With Ekitiké and Gyökeres already secured, this completes a strong forward line early, allowing me to prioritize midfielders and defenders in subsequent rounds while top attackers are still being drafted heavily.

Neto is the highest-ranked available player (rank 32) in a position I need (MID), offering excellent value as a premium winger for Chelsea. With back-to-back picks, I can secure another top player next, balancing my needs for DEF and GK while prioritizing quality.
